<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="FRQ1B-Part2">
<title>FRQ 1B - Strings - Part 2</title>
<introduction>
<idx>frq1-methods</idx>
<idx>frq1b-strings</idx>
<idx>free response</idx>
<p>From the 2025 Course and Exam Description: </p>
    <p><term>Free-Response Question 1: Methods and Control Structures</term>. Students will write two methods or one constructor and one method of a given class based on the provided specifications and examples. In Part A (4 points), the method or constructor will require students to write iterative or conditional statements, or both, as well as statements that call methods in the specified class. </p>
    <p>In Part B (3 points)<term></term>, the method or constructor will require calling String methods.</p>

<p>FRQ 1B requires the following skills:</p>
<ul>
<li>Complete a method or a constructor</li>
<li>Call String methods</li>
<li>Use if statements</li>
<li>Use a for loop or a while loop</li>
</ul>

<p>Teacher Insights</p>
<ul>
    <li>You do not need to include import statements. You can assume that any standard Java class is already imported.</li>
<li>You will NEVER print. If you think you need to print, you probably need to return something.</li>
<li>You will NOT need to write a main.</li>
</ul>
</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b2-string-algorithms">
<title>String Algorithms</title>
<p>There are many algorithms that traverse or process Strings that use loops and conditional statements.</p>
<p>Common algorithms include:</p>

<ul>
<li>Counting the number of substrings that meet specific criteria</li>
<li>Determining if one or more substrings has a specific property</li>
<li>Building a new String based on certain conditions</li>
</ul>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b2-processing-strings">
<title>Processing a String with a For Loop</title>
<p>Many algorithms can be solved with the accumulator pattern, similar to FRQ1A. In some cases, the accumulator value will be a String.</p>
<p>There are four steps to the accumulator pattern:</p>
<ul>
<li>initialize the accumulator variable before the loop</li>
<li>loop through the letters of the String</li>
<li>update the accumulator variable inside the loop</li>
<li>return the accumulated value (if necessary)</li>
</ul>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b2-countVowels">
<title>String Algorithm - Count Vowels</title>

<activity label="frq1b2-countVowels">
<statement>
<p>You are working on a text-analysis tool. The StringProcessor class contains a helper method, isVowel(String letter), which returns true if a single-character string is a vowel (A, E, I, O, U, case-insensitive) and false otherwise.</p>
<p>Write the countVowels method. This method analyzes a given String and returns the total number of vowels present in that string.</p>
</statement>

<program interactive="activecode" language="java">
<code>
public class StringProcessor {
    // Corrected method name and parameter type
    public static int countVowels(String phrase) {
        
    }

    public static boolean isVowel(String letter) {
        String vowels = "aeiouAEIOU";
        return letter.length() == 1 &amp;&amp; vowels.contains(letter);
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test 1: Standard sentence
        String s1 = "Java Programming";
        System.out.println("Phrase: " + s1);
        System.out.println("Vowels: " + StringProcessor.countVowels(s1)); // Expected: 5
        System.out.println();

        // Test 2: All uppercase
        String s2 = "AEIOU";
        System.out.println("Phrase: " + s2);
        System.out.println("Vowels: " + StringProcessor.countVowels(s2)); // Expected: 5
        System.out.println();

        // Test 3: No vowels
        String s3 = "Rhythm";
        System.out.println("Phrase: " + s3);
        System.out.println("Vowels: " + StringProcessor.countVowels(s3)); // Expected: 0
    }
}
</code>
<tests>
import static org.junit.Assert.*;
import org.junit.*;
import java.io.*;

public class RunestoneTests extends CodeTestHelper
{
    private String[] input = {"Apple", "12345!", "", " ", "Queueing"};
    private String[] expected = {"2", "0", "0", "0", "5"};

    @Test
    public void test0() {
        boolean passed = test(0);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }

    @Test
    public void test1() {
        boolean passed = test(1);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }

    @Test
    public void test2() {
        boolean passed = test(2);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }

    @Test
    public void test3() {
        boolean passed = test(3);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }

    @Test
    public void test4() {
        boolean passed = test(4);
        assertTrue(passed);
    }

    private boolean test(int i) {
        String desc = "swapTwoWords(\"" + input[i] + "\")";
        String actual = "";

        try {
            actual = "" + StringProcessor.countVowels(input[i]);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            actual = "The code caused an exception";
        }

        boolean passed = getResults(expected[i],actual,desc);
        return passed;        
    }

    private boolean stringMatch(String str1, String str2) {
        str1 = str1.replaceAll(" ", "");
        str2 = str2.replaceAll(" ", "");

        return str1.contains(str2);
    }
}
</tests>
</program>
</activity>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="frq1b2-makeAbbreviation">
<title>String Algorithm - Make Abbreviation</title>

<activity label="frq1b2-makeAbbreviation">
<statement>
<p>Write a method called makeAbbreviation that takes a multi-word String and returns a new String consisting of the first letter of each word in uppercase.</p>
</statement>

<program interactive="activecode" language="java">
<code>
public class Abbreviator {

    public static String makeAbbreviation(String phrase) {
        String result = "";

        // Write Your Code Here

        return result.toUpperCase();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Driver examples
        System.out.println("Input: self contained underwater breathing apparatus");
        System.out.println("Result: " + makeAbbreviation("self contained underwater breathing apparatus"));

        System.out.println("\nInput: North Atlantic Treaty Organization");
        System.out.println("Result: " + makeAbbreviation("North Atlantic Treaty Organization"));

        System.out.println("Input: 'z'");
        System.out.println("Result: " + Abbreviator.makeAbbreviation("z")); 
        
        System.out.println("Input: '3 blind mice'");
        System.out.println("Result: " + Abbreviator.makeAbbreviation("3 blind mice"));
    }
}
</code>
<tests>
